{"parentUuid":null,"isSidechain":true,"promptId":"dcbe4efb-6e32-4db6-a75a-aa49b911d737","agentId":"a6867b8fa220460c5","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":"You are a web research agent. Use WebSearch and WebFetch (load them via ToolSearch query \"select:WebSearch,WebFetch\" first if not available). The current date is June 2026.\n\nRESEARCH ANGLE: Realistic outlook/timeline for small local models becoming \"good enough to self-improve their own codebase,\" and the trend of small-model coding capability over time.\n\nResearch concretely:\n- The rate of improvement of small (7-8B) open models at coding over 2023->2026 (Qwen2.5-Coder vs Qwen3 vs Qwen3-Coder; how fast SWE-bench/LiveCodeBench scores for small models are rising). Is the gap to frontier closing or widening?\n- METR's \"task length doubling\" / time-horizon trend (length of tasks AI can do autonomously doubling ~every 7 months) — implications for autonomous multi-step coding.\n- Predictions/timelines for autonomous AI software engineering, recursive self-improvement timelines (AI 2027, lab statements, expert forecasts).\n- Local/on-device AI coding trends: are small models trending toward usable autonomous agents locally, and what techniques (distillation, RL, agentic scaffolding, longer context) drive it.\n- Realistic skeptic takes: why small local models still fail at autonomous self-coding (context limits, long-horizon reliability, error compounding).\n\nRun at least 4-5 searches. Fetch authoritative sources (METR blog metr.org, arXiv, lab blogs, Qwen release posts, Epoch AI). Cross-check.\n\nReturn a list of FALSIFIABLE CLAIMS each with: claim, number/detail, source URL. Flag conflicts. Do NOT write files. Return findings only as your final message."},"uuid":"3f5a8823-c09d-41cf-afed-b0da12b65627","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:34:55.167Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main",