{"parentUuid":"95ca1134-8234-46fc-8240-f047779cf14b","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"dcbe4efb-6e32-4db6-a75a-aa49b911d737","agentId":"a6867b8fa220460c5","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01PQE6FzgPURYqeCiNVwHFXN","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"Qwen3-Coder vs Qwen2.5-Coder SWE-bench LiveCodeBench small model coding improvement 2025\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"Qwen3 Coder: Agentic Coding Assistant in the World\",\"url\":\"https://qwen3lm.com/qwen-coder/\"},{\"title\":\"Qwen AI Review 2025: Best Qwen Model for Coding | Qwen Coder Tested | Index.dev\",\"url\":\"https://www.index.dev/blog/qwen-ai-coding-review\"},{\"title\":\"Qwen3-Coder-Next Technical Report\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2603.00729v1\"},{\"title\":\"Qwen 3 vs Qwen2.5-Coder: Which is Better for Programming? | BSWEN\",\"url\":\"https://docs.bswen.com/blog/2026-03-27-qwen3-vs-qwen25-coder-programming/\"},{\"title\":\"Qwen3-Coder: A Deep Dive Review With Benchmarks & Real-World Tests\",\"url\":\"https://binaryverseai.com/qwen3-coder-review/\"},{\"title\":\"2026-03-03 Qwen3-Coder-Next Technical Report Qwen Team\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2603.00729\"},{\"title\":\"Qwen3-Coder-Next: Pushing Small Hybrid Models\",\"url\":\"https://qwen.ai/blog?id=qwen3-coder-next\"},{\"title\":\"Best Open Source Self-Hosted LLMs for Coding in 2026 - Pinggy\",\"url\":\"https://pinggy.io/blog/best_open_source_self_hosted_llms_for_coding/\"}]\n\nBased on the search results, here's what I found about Qwen3-Coder vs Qwen2.5-Coder:\n\n## Key Differences\n\n**Training Approach:**\nRather than scaling model size, Qwen3-Coder takes a different approach by scaling agentic training, with the model specifically post-trained on long-horizon software engineering tasks including multi-file edits, test-driven debugging cycles, and codebase navigation.\n\n## Performance on Benchmarks\n\n**SWE-Bench Results:**\nQwen3-Coder-Next achieves scores of 70.6% with SWE-Agent, 71.1% with MiniSWE-Agent, and 71.3% with OpenHands. Despite its small active footprint (3B active), Qwen3-Coder-Next achieves SWE-Bench Pro performance comparable to models with 10×–20× more active parameters.\n\nIn comparison, Qwen2.5-Coder-32B-Instruct matches GPT-4o on EvalPlus, LiveCodeBench, and BigCodeBench, and scores 73.7 on the Aider code-repair benchmark.\n\n## Small Model Improvements\n\nQwen3-Coder-Next's key highlight is its exceptional efficiency—despite its relatively compact size of 80A3, it achieves results that are on par with, and in some cases outperform, much larger models.\n\n**Practical Use Cases:**\nFor most developers in 2025-2026, Qwen3 is the better investment because its reasoning capabilities make it more useful for real programming work, though the performance gap for pure coding tasks is small.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"d5fefa59-3adb-46b9-bff2-5e69578d392e","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:35:11.388Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"Qwen3-Coder vs Qwen2.5-Coder SWE-bench LiveCodeBench small model coding improvement 2025","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_012uzKYrJugzqx25YdWBtaeL","content":[{"title":"Qwen3 Coder: Agentic Coding Assistant in the World","url":"https://qwen3lm.com/qwen-coder/"},{"title":"Qwen AI Review 2025: Best Qwen Model for Coding | Qwen Coder Tested | Index.dev","url":"https://www.index.dev/blog/qwen-ai-coding-review"},{"title":"Qwen3-Coder-Next Technical Report","url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2603.00729v1"},{"title":"Qwen 3 vs Qwen2.5-Coder: Which is Better for Programming? | BSWEN","url":"https://docs.bswen.com/blog/2026-03-27-qwen3-vs-qwen25-coder-programming/"},{"title":"Qwen3-Coder: A Deep Dive Review With Benchmarks & Real-World Tests","url":"https://binaryverseai.com/qwen3-coder-review/"},{"title":"2026-03-03 Qwen3-Coder-Next Technical Report Qwen Team","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2603.00729"},{"title":"Qwen3-Coder-Next: Pushing Small Hybrid Models","url":"https://qwen.ai/blog?id=qwen3-coder-next"},{"title":"Best Open Source Self-Hosted LLMs for Coding in 2026 - Pinggy","url":"https://pinggy.io/blog/best_open_source_self_hosted_llms_for_coding/"}]},"Based on the search results, here's what I found about Qwen3-Coder vs Qwen2.5-Coder:\n\n## Key Differences\n\n**Training Approach:**\nRather than scaling model size, Qwen3-Coder takes a different approach by scaling agentic training, with the model specifically post-trained on long-horizon software engineering tasks including multi-file edits, test-driven debugging cycles, and codebase navigation.\n\n## Performance on Benchmarks\n\n**SWE-Bench Results:**\nQwen3-Coder-Next achieves scores of 70.6% with SWE-Agent, 71.1% with MiniSWE-Agent, and 71.3% with OpenHands. Despite its small active footprint (3B active), Qwen3-Coder-Next achieves SWE-Bench Pro performance comparable to models with 10×–20× more active parameters.\n\nIn comparison, Qwen2.5-Coder-32B-Instruct matches GPT-4o on EvalPlus, LiveCodeBench, and BigCodeBench, and scores 73.7 on the Aider code-repair benchmark.\n\n## Small Model Improvements\n\nQwen3-Coder-Next's key highlight is its exceptional efficiency—despite its relatively compact size of 80A3, it achieves results that are on par with, and in some cases outperform, much larger models.\n\n**Practical Use Cases:**\nFor most developers in 2025-2026, Qwen3 is the better investment because its reasoning capabilities make it more useful for real programming work, though the performance gap for pure coding tasks is small."],"durationSeconds":8.288845375001431,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"95ca1134-8234-46fc-8240-f047779cf14b","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"3213b05c-c5f0-4c81-8286-df3145e66aa6","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"dcbe4efb-6e32-4db6-a75a-aa49b911d737","agentId":"a6867b8fa220460c5","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01E2VUzXLP2s4JWxf1fg35VY","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"METR task length doubling time horizon AI autonomous tasks 7 months trend 2025 2026\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"Time Horizon 1.1 - METR\",\"url\":\"https://metr.org/blog/2026-1-29-time-horizon-1-1/\"},{\"title\":\"How Does Time Horizon Vary Across Domains? - METR\",\"url\":\"https://metr.org/blog/2025-07-14-how-does-time-horizon-vary-across-domains/\"},{\"title\":\"Measuring AI Ability to Complete Long Tasks - METR\",\"url\":\"https://metr.org/blog/2025-03-19-measuring-ai-ability-to-complete-long-tasks/\"},{\"title\":\"A new Moore's Law for AI agents - AI Digest\",\"url\":\"https://theaidigest.org/time-horizons\"},{\"title\":\"Are AI time-horizons (still) doubling every 7 months? | by Anatol Wegner | Medium\",\"url\":\"https://medium.com/@AIchats/are-ai-time-horizons-still-doubling-every-7-months-6262ed2bcc6a\"},{\"title\":\"Is there a half-life for the success rates of AI agents?\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2505.05115\"},{\"title\":\"Are AI time horizon doubling every seven months? | by Anatol Wegner | Medium\",\"url\":\"https://medium.com/@AIchats/are-ai-time-horizon-doubling-every-seven-months-e337162eec83\"},{\"title\":\"Measuring AI Ability to Complete Long Tasks\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/html/2503.14499v1\"}]\n\nBased on the search results, here's what I found about METR's research on task length doubling time horizon for AI autonomous tasks:\n\n## Key Findings\n\nEarly in 2025, METR published their time-horizon methodology for measuring the autonomous capabilities of AI models and found a steady exponential increase in models' human-equivalent \"time horizon\" over the course of 2025.\n\n### The 7-Month Doubling Time\n\nMETR's original time horizon dataset released in March 2025 showed a smooth trend with the frontier time-horizon doubling around every 7 months over the period 2019 to 2025. Extrapolating this trend predicts that in under a decade, we will see AI agents that can independently complete a large fraction of software tasks that currently take humans days or weeks.\n\n### Recent Acceleration\n\nHowever, there's evidence the trend may be accelerating. In 2024-2025, time horizons doubled every 4 months, down from every 7 months over 2019-2025.\n\n### Updated Methodology (2026)\n\nMETR increased the tasks in their suite by 34% (228/170) and doubled the number of tasks that are 8 hours or longer (31/14) in their Time Horizon 1.1 update released in January 2026, which provides improved confidence intervals for measuring more recent models' capabilities.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"9f8e0690-414c-4d58-b632-d3bba46e8271","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:35:11.693Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"METR task length doubling time horizon AI autonomous tasks 7 months trend 2025 2026","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_01QzU33k94kc8L18Q5mc1qk1","content":[{"title":"Time Horizon 1.1 - METR","url":"https://metr.org/blog/2026-1-29-time-horizon-1-1/"},{"title":"How Does Time Horizon Vary Across Domains? - METR","url":"https://metr.org/blog/2025-07-14-how-does-time-horizon-vary-across-domains/"},{"title":"Measuring AI Ability to Complete Long Tasks - METR","url":"https://metr.org/blog/2025-03-19-measuring-ai-ability-to-complete-long-tasks/"},{"title":"A new Moore's Law for AI agents - AI Digest","url":"https://theaidigest.org/time-horizons"},{"title":"Are AI time-horizons (still) doubling every 7 months? | by Anatol Wegner | Medium","url":"https://medium.com/@AIchats/are-ai-time-horizons-still-doubling-every-7-months-6262ed2bcc6a"},{"title":"Is there a half-life for the success rates of AI agents?","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2505.05115"},{"title":"Are AI time horizon doubling every seven months? | by Anatol Wegner | Medium","url":"https://medium.com/@AIchats/are-ai-time-horizon-doubling-every-seven-months-e337162eec83"},{"title":"Measuring AI Ability to Complete Long Tasks","url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2503.14499v1"}]},"Based on the search results, here's what I found about METR's research on task length doubling time horizon for AI autonomous tasks:\n\n## Key Findings\n\nEarly in 2025, METR published their time-horizon methodology for measuring the autonomous capabilities of AI models and found a steady exponential increase in models' human-equivalent \"time horizon\" over the course of 2025.\n\n### The 7-Month Doubling Time\n\nMETR's original time horizon dataset released in March 2025 showed a smooth trend with the frontier time-horizon doubling around every 7 months over the period 2019 to 2025. Extrapolating this trend predicts that in under a decade, we will see AI agents that can independently complete a large fraction of software tasks that currently take humans days or weeks.\n\n### Recent Acceleration\n\nHowever, there's evidence the trend may be accelerating. In 2024-2025, time horizons doubled every 4 months, down from every 7 months over 2019-2025.\n\n### Updated Methodology (2026)\n\nMETR increased the tasks in their suite by 34% (228/170) and doubled the number of tasks that are 8 hours or longer (31/14) in their Time Horizon 1.1 update released in January 2026, which provides improved confidence intervals for measuring more recent models' capabilities."],"durationSeconds":7.6323430420011285,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"3213b05c-c5f0-4c81-8286-df3145e66aa6","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"2b6c5039-e9bb-4f2a-9349-55b9c55dc147","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"dcbe4efb-6e32-4db6-a75a-aa49b911d737","agentId":"a6867b8fa220460c5","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01YCtCEYddZwgBceFcTjNSsu","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"AI 2027 recursive self-improvement autonomous software engineering timeline forecast\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"Will We See AI with Recursive Self Improvement in 2028? Likely Not.\",\"url\":\"https://hashcollision.substack.com/p/will-we-see-ai-with-recursive-self\"},{\"title\":\"AI Recursive Self-Improvement: Anthropic Co-Founder Predicts 60% Chance by 2028 | Claude API\",\"url\":\"https://www.claudeapi.com/en/blog/news/ai-recursive-self-improvement-2028-prediction/\"},{\"title\":\"AI Futures Project Delays Timeline of 2030 Human Apocalypse Scenario - Hungarian Conservative\",\"url\":\"https://www.hungarianconservative.com/articles/tech/ai-futures-project-ai-2027-apocalypse-timeline-superintelligence-daniel-kokotajlo/\"},{\"title\":\"AI 2027\",\"url\":\"https://ai-2027.com/\"},{\"title\":\"When AI builds itself \\\\ Anthropic\",\"url\":\"https://www.anthropic.com/institute/recursive-self-improvement\"},{\"title\":\"AI Futures Project - Wikipedia\",\"url\":\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/AI_Futures_Project\"},{\"title\":\"Will Compute Bottlenecks Prevent an Intelligence Explosion?\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2507.23181\"},{\"title\":\"Recursive Self Improvement is SIX MONTHS away!\",\"url\":\"https://daveshap.substack.com/p/recursive-self-improvement-is-six\"}]\n\nBased on the web search results, here's what I found regarding AI 2027, recursive self-improvement, and autonomous software engineering timelines:\n\n## Key Forecasts and Predictions\n\nThere's a 60% or higher chance that by the end of 2028 an AI system will be powerful enough to autonomously build its own successor, with a 30% chance as early as 2027. The 30% for 2027 reflects a scenario where \"engineering automation is largely complete but the creativity gap remains open.\"\n\nThe AI Futures Project, led by former OpenAI researcher Daniel Kokotajlo, has revised its forecast for superintelligent AI, concluding that technological breakthroughs once expected by 2027 are now more likely to arrive in the early 2030s. However, the original AI 2027 report projected that breakthroughs in autonomous artificial intelligence agents and recursive self-improvement could produce systems that far exceed human cognitive abilities by the end of 2027.\n\n## Supporting Arguments and Counterarguments\n\nThe forecast rests on rapid progress in coding, longer agentic task horizons, scientific-reproduction benchmarks, kernel optimization, automated post-training, multi-agent management, and early examples of AI contributing to mathematics and alignment research.\n\nHowever, there is an important distinction between partial automation and reliable, full-stack autonomy—automating pieces of AI R&D is not the same as autonomously running the entire frontier-model improvement pipeline.\n\n## Current Progress\n\nAt Anthropic, they are delegating a growing share of AI development to AI systems themselves, and taken far enough with enough compute, that trend points to an AI system capable of fully autonomously designing and developing its own successor.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"48e7182c-7513-4a32-88bb-e955449a26d1","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:35:13.365Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"AI 2027 recursive self-improvement autonomous software engineering timeline forecast","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_01G7dcmqSJCpkwBg3e57TZ4k","content":[{"title":"Will We See AI with Recursive Self Improvement in 2028? Likely Not.","url":"https://hashcollision.substack.com/p/will-we-see-ai-with-recursive-self"},{"title":"AI Recursive Self-Improvement: Anthropic Co-Founder Predicts 60% Chance by 2028 | Claude API","url":"https://www.claudeapi.com/en/blog/news/ai-recursive-self-improvement-2028-prediction/"},{"title":"AI Futures Project Delays Timeline of 2030 Human Apocalypse Scenario - Hungarian Conservative","url":"https://www.hungarianconservative.com/articles/tech/ai-futures-project-ai-2027-apocalypse-timeline-superintelligence-daniel-kokotajlo/"},{"title":"AI 2027","url":"https://ai-2027.com/"},{"title":"When AI builds itself \\ Anthropic","url":"https://www.anthropic.com/institute/recursive-self-improvement"},{"title":"AI Futures Project - Wikipedia","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/AI_Futures_Project"},{"title":"Will Compute Bottlenecks Prevent an Intelligence Explosion?","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2507.23181"},{"title":"Recursive Self Improvement is SIX MONTHS away!","url":"https://daveshap.substack.com/p/recursive-self-improvement-is-six"}]},"Based on the web search results, here's what I found regarding AI 2027, recursive self-improvement, and autonomous software engineering timelines:\n\n## Key Forecasts and Predictions\n\nThere's a 60% or higher chance that by the end of 2028 an AI system will be powerful enough to autonomously build its own successor, with a 30% chance as early as 2027. The 30% for 2027 reflects a scenario where \"engineering automation is largely complete but the creativity gap remains open.\"\n\nThe AI Futures Project, led by former OpenAI researcher Daniel Kokotajlo, has revised its forecast for superintelligent AI, concluding that technological breakthroughs once expected by 2027 are now more likely to arrive in the early 2030s. However, the original AI 2027 report projected that breakthroughs in autonomous artificial intelligence agents and recursive self-improvement could produce systems that far exceed human cognitive abilities by the end of 2027.\n\n## Supporting Arguments and Counterarguments\n\nThe forecast rests on rapid progress in coding, longer agentic task horizons, scientific-reproduction benchmarks, kernel optimization, automated post-training, multi-agent management, and early examples of AI contributing to mathematics and alignment research.\n\nHowever, there is an important distinction between partial automation and reliable, full-stack autonomy—automating pieces of AI R&D is not the same as autonomously running the entire frontier-model improvement pipeline.\n\n## Current Progress\n\nAt Anthropic, they are delegating a growing share of AI development to AI systems themselves, and taken far enough with enough compute, that trend points to an AI system capable of fully autonomously designing and developing its own successor."],"durationSeconds":8.797215250000358,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"2b6c5039-e9bb-4f2a-9349-55b9c55dc147","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
