{"parentUuid":"1332eb2f-8929-4868-ac45-d24d9bbd76b0","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"dcbe4efb-6e32-4db6-a75a-aa49b911d737","agentId":"a6867b8fa220460c5","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01WcZVeN8kpLtgZwpruQw14U","type":"tool_result","content":"# Time Horizon 1.1 Key Numbers\n\n**Frontier Model Time Horizons:**\n- Claude Opus 4.5: \"320 [170,729]\" minutes (approximately 5.3 hours at the point estimate)\n- GPT-5: \"214 [117,480]\" minutes (approximately 3.6 hours)\n- o3: \"121 [74,201]\" minutes (approximately 2 hours)\n\n**Doubling Rate:**\nThe overall trend shows \"a smooth trend with the frontier time-horizon doubling around every 7 months\" historically. However, recent acceleration exists: since 2024, the doubling rate is \"88.6 days\" (roughly 3 months) under TH1.1, down from \"108.9 days\" under TH1.\n\n**Frontier Models:**\nThe document identifies Claude Opus 4.5, GPT-5, and o3 as leading the capability frontier based on their highest time horizon estimates.\n\n**Success Rate Horizons:**\nThe document reports \"50%-time-horizon\" measurements but does not provide separate 80% success rate horizon figures. All estimates presented use median (50th percentile) calculations with confidence intervals rather than multiple success thresholds.\n\n**Note:** The document uses \"P50 doubling time\" terminology, indicating median doubling estimates rather than discussing multiple confidence levels for success rates."}]},"uuid":"b2d72adf-3ab3-4537-a639-4681b2f39dee","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:35:29.829Z","toolUseResult":{"bytes":62244,"code":200,"codeText":"OK","result":"# Time Horizon 1.1 Key Numbers\n\n**Frontier Model Time Horizons:**\n- Claude Opus 4.5: \"320 [170,729]\" minutes (approximately 5.3 hours at the point estimate)\n- GPT-5: \"214 [117,480]\" minutes (approximately 3.6 hours)\n- o3: \"121 [74,201]\" minutes (approximately 2 hours)\n\n**Doubling Rate:**\nThe overall trend shows \"a smooth trend with the frontier time-horizon doubling around every 7 months\" historically. However, recent acceleration exists: since 2024, the doubling rate is \"88.6 days\" (roughly 3 months) under TH1.1, down from \"108.9 days\" under TH1.\n\n**Frontier Models:**\nThe document identifies Claude Opus 4.5, GPT-5, and o3 as leading the capability frontier based on their highest time horizon estimates.\n\n**Success Rate Horizons:**\nThe document reports \"50%-time-horizon\" measurements but does not provide separate 80% success rate horizon figures. All estimates presented use median (50th percentile) calculations with confidence intervals rather than multiple success thresholds.\n\n**Note:** The document uses \"P50 doubling time\" terminology, indicating median doubling estimates rather than discussing multiple confidence levels for success rates.","durationMs":6723,"url":"https://metr.org/blog/2026-1-29-time-horizon-1-1/"},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"1332eb2f-8929-4868-ac45-d24d9bbd76b0","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"157e7cc4-12a1-497c-8854-5385ef712614","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"dcbe4efb-6e32-4db6-a75a-aa49b911d737","agentId":"a6867b8fa220460c5","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_015QHPqCwJiJLjSsqmWaREAm","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"small local LLM on-device coding agent distillation reinforcement learning trend 2026 7B autonomous\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"LLM Knowledge Distillation Explained for On-Device AI - Enclave AI - Private, Local, Offline AI Assistant for MacOS and iOS\",\"url\":\"https://enclaveai.app/blog/2026/03/29/llm-knowledge-distillation-on-device-explained/\"},{\"title\":\"MiniCPM5–1B : The Best Small LLM Ever | by Mehul Gupta | Data Science in Your Pocket | May, 2026 | Medium\",\"url\":\"https://medium.com/data-science-in-your-pocket/minicpm5-1b-the-best-small-llm-ever-7c36d565f4df\"},{\"title\":\"Structured Agent Distillation for Large Language Model\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2505.13820\"},{\"title\":\"Top 5 Local LLM Tools and Models in 2026 - Pinggy\",\"url\":\"https://pinggy.io/blog/top_5_local_llm_tools_and_models/\"},{\"title\":\"The Best LLMs for Agentic Coding in 2026 (Real-World, Not Just Benchmarks) - DEV Community\",\"url\":\"https://dev.to/danishashko/the-best-llms-for-agentic-coding-in-2026-real-world-not-just-benchmarks-96n\"},{\"title\":\"The Complete Guide to Running Local LLMs in 2026\",\"url\":\"https://www.kunalganglani.com/blog/local-llms-complete-guide\"},{\"title\":\"Best Open-Source LLM Models in 2026: Coding, Local, Agentic AI, Benchmarks, and License\",\"url\":\"https://huggingface.co/blog/daya-shankar/open-source-llms\"},{\"title\":\"[2505.17612] Distilling LLM Agent into Small Models with Retrieval and Code Tools\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2505.17612\"}]\n\nBased on the web search results, here's what's happening with small local LLM on-device coding agents in 2026:\n\n## Knowledge Distillation & Model Optimization\n\nIn 2026 vendors want flagship-quality answers without shipping a 400-billion-parameter file to every device, and LLM knowledge distillation is a training technique where a small \"student\" model learns to imitate a much larger \"teacher\" model — so the student can run on a phone or laptop while still behaving more like the big model.\n\nNews cycles in early 2026 have highlighted partnerships and distillation pipelines between platform companies and large cloud model providers — the pattern is structural: big teacher in the datacenter, small student in the pocket.\n\n## Real-World Examples: MiniCPM5-1B & Agent Distillation\n\nMiniCPM5–1B is a dense 1B parameter Transformer model built mainly for local deployment, edge AI, coding agents, and on-device assistants. MiniCPM5–1B combines RL and OPD together, and according to OpenBMB, this produced average score improvement across math, code, and instruction-following tasks.\n\nAgent Distillation is a framework for transferring not only reasoning capability but full task-solving behavior from LLM-based agents into sLMs with retrieval and code tools.\n\n## Broader Trend: Local & Agentic Coding\n\nDeepSeek V4, Qwen 3 Coder, and Kimi K2.6 are within a few benchmark points of frontier models at a fraction of the cost, and the open-weight tier is now good enough that lots of teams run 60 to 80 percent of their agent traffic locally and only escalate the hard 20 percent to a frontier API.\n\nOpen-source AI in 2026 is no longer just the cheaper alternative to closed models. For coding, reasoning, agentic workflows, long-context analysis, and local deployment, open-weight models are now good enough for serious production use.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"71fdb77e-98ce-4c33-a04d-458769d67782","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:35:34.400Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"small local LLM on-device coding agent distillation reinforcement learning trend 2026 7B autonomous","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_01KTRksR14VqLDhVsFDep2EV","content":[{"title":"LLM Knowledge Distillation Explained for On-Device AI - Enclave AI - Private, Local, Offline AI Assistant for MacOS and iOS","url":"https://enclaveai.app/blog/2026/03/29/llm-knowledge-distillation-on-device-explained/"},{"title":"MiniCPM5–1B : The Best Small LLM Ever | by Mehul Gupta | Data Science in Your Pocket | May, 2026 | Medium","url":"https://medium.com/data-science-in-your-pocket/minicpm5-1b-the-best-small-llm-ever-7c36d565f4df"},{"title":"Structured Agent Distillation for Large Language Model","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2505.13820"},{"title":"Top 5 Local LLM Tools and Models in 2026 - Pinggy","url":"https://pinggy.io/blog/top_5_local_llm_tools_and_models/"},{"title":"The Best LLMs for Agentic Coding in 2026 (Real-World, Not Just Benchmarks) - DEV Community","url":"https://dev.to/danishashko/the-best-llms-for-agentic-coding-in-2026-real-world-not-just-benchmarks-96n"},{"title":"The Complete Guide to Running Local LLMs in 2026","url":"https://www.kunalganglani.com/blog/local-llms-complete-guide"},{"title":"Best Open-Source LLM Models in 2026: Coding, Local, Agentic AI, Benchmarks, and License","url":"https://huggingface.co/blog/daya-shankar/open-source-llms"},{"title":"[2505.17612] Distilling LLM Agent into Small Models with Retrieval and Code Tools","url":"https://arxiv.org/abs/2505.17612"}]},"Based on the web search results, here's what's happening with small local LLM on-device coding agents in 2026:\n\n## Knowledge Distillation & Model Optimization\n\nIn 2026 vendors want flagship-quality answers without shipping a 400-billion-parameter file to every device, and LLM knowledge distillation is a training technique where a small \"student\" model learns to imitate a much larger \"teacher\" model — so the student can run on a phone or laptop while still behaving more like the big model.\n\nNews cycles in early 2026 have highlighted partnerships and distillation pipelines between platform companies and large cloud model providers — the pattern is structural: big teacher in the datacenter, small student in the pocket.\n\n## Real-World Examples: MiniCPM5-1B & Agent Distillation\n\nMiniCPM5–1B is a dense 1B parameter Transformer model built mainly for local deployment, edge AI, coding agents, and on-device assistants. MiniCPM5–1B combines RL and OPD together, and according to OpenBMB, this produced average score improvement across math, code, and instruction-following tasks.\n\nAgent Distillation is a framework for transferring not only reasoning capability but full task-solving behavior from LLM-based agents into sLMs with retrieval and code tools.\n\n## Broader Trend: Local & Agentic Coding\n\nDeepSeek V4, Qwen 3 Coder, and Kimi K2.6 are within a few benchmark points of frontier models at a fraction of the cost, and the open-weight tier is now good enough that lots of teams run 60 to 80 percent of their agent traffic locally and only escalate the hard 20 percent to a frontier API.\n\nOpen-source AI in 2026 is no longer just the cheaper alternative to closed models. For coding, reasoning, agentic workflows, long-context analysis, and local deployment, open-weight models are now good enough for serious production use."],"durationSeconds":10.432767291000113,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"157e7cc4-12a1-497c-8854-5385ef712614","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"41594bb8-650d-4720-a849-bfd080f1443e","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"dcbe4efb-6e32-4db6-a75a-aa49b911d737","agentId":"a6867b8fa220460c5","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01JnTg3Qqb1AX2Q9QWDo6R65","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"why small local models fail autonomous coding long horizon reliability error compounding context limits\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"PARC: An Autonomous Self-Reflective Coding Agent for Robust Execution of Long-Horizon Tasks\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2512.03549\"},{\"title\":\"Best Open Source LLMs In 2026: Benchmarks, Licenses And GPU Deployment Guide\",\"url\":\"https://acecloud.ai/blog/best-open-source-llms/\"},{\"title\":\"Best Open-Source LLM Models in 2026: Coding, Local, Agentic AI, Benchmarks, and License\",\"url\":\"https://huggingface.co/blog/daya-shankar/open-source-llms\"},{\"title\":\"Local AI Agents in 2026: What Actually Works (And What Still Fails)\",\"url\":\"https://www.promptquorum.com/power-local-llm/autonomous-local-agents-actually-work\"},{\"title\":\"The Best Open-Source LLMs for Agentic Coding in 2026 | MindStudio\",\"url\":\"https://www.mindstudio.ai/blog/best-open-source-llms-agentic-coding-2026\"},{\"title\":\"Top 5 Small AI Coding Models That You Can Run Locally - KDnuggets\",\"url\":\"https://www.kdnuggets.com/top-5-small-ai-coding-models-that-you-can-run-locally\"},{\"title\":\"Beyond pass@1: A Reliability Science Framework for Long-Horizon LLM Agents\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2603.29231\"},{\"title\":\"The Best Open-Source LLMs in 2026\",\"url\":\"https://www.bentoml.com/blog/navigating-the-world-of-open-source-large-language-models\"}]\n\nBased on the search results, here are the key findings about why small local models fail at autonomous coding with long-horizon tasks:\n\n## Context Window and Information Overflow\n\nCoding agents often fail when logs, file diffs, tool outputs and previous reasoning steps overflow the context window. Small local models typically have limited context windows, making them unable to maintain the full state needed for extended tasks.\n\n## Reliability Decay Over Task Horizons\n\nReliability decay is universal and pronounced, with all 10 models showing net decline in pass@1 from short to very-long horizons, with a mean drop of 24.3 percentage points (76.3% → 52.1%) over the four-bucket span. This demonstrates how error compounding becomes increasingly problematic as tasks extend.\n\n## Long-Horizon Planning Failures\n\nFrameworks pitched as \"fully autonomous\" still drift into circular tool calls, hallucinate file paths, or get stuck on long-horizon planning. Smaller models lack the capacity for sophisticated planning needed across multiple steps.\n\n## Model Capability Thresholds\n\nModels like Qwen3-Coder 30B, GLM-5.1 32B, Gemma 4 27B, and Llama 3.3 70B emit clean tool calls in every reliable stack, while models under 7B fail. This indicates a significant capability gap below certain parameter thresholds.\n\n## Practical Limitations of \"Autonomous\" Systems\n\nReliable stacks like Cline + Ollama and Continue.dev Agent mode succeed because they are scoped—one editor, one model, one approval gate—not because the underlying technology is good enough for unattended autonomy.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"bbd2b6f7-b844-4aa9-8e09-3499bf02bec9","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:35:36.140Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"why small local models fail autonomous coding long horizon reliability error compounding context limits","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_01VJdDRcPPShC4pXxedEMLLA","content":[{"title":"PARC: An Autonomous Self-Reflective Coding Agent for Robust Execution of Long-Horizon Tasks","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2512.03549"},{"title":"Best Open Source LLMs In 2026: Benchmarks, Licenses And GPU Deployment Guide","url":"https://acecloud.ai/blog/best-open-source-llms/"},{"title":"Best Open-Source LLM Models in 2026: Coding, Local, Agentic AI, Benchmarks, and License","url":"https://huggingface.co/blog/daya-shankar/open-source-llms"},{"title":"Local AI Agents in 2026: What Actually Works (And What Still Fails)","url":"https://www.promptquorum.com/power-local-llm/autonomous-local-agents-actually-work"},{"title":"The Best Open-Source LLMs for Agentic Coding in 2026 | MindStudio","url":"https://www.mindstudio.ai/blog/best-open-source-llms-agentic-coding-2026"},{"title":"Top 5 Small AI Coding Models That You Can Run Locally - KDnuggets","url":"https://www.kdnuggets.com/top-5-small-ai-coding-models-that-you-can-run-locally"},{"title":"Beyond pass@1: A Reliability Science Framework for Long-Horizon LLM Agents","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2603.29231"},{"title":"The Best Open-Source LLMs in 2026","url":"https://www.bentoml.com/blog/navigating-the-world-of-open-source-large-language-models"}]},"Based on the search results, here are the key findings about why small local models fail at autonomous coding with long-horizon tasks:\n\n## Context Window and Information Overflow\n\nCoding agents often fail when logs, file diffs, tool outputs and previous reasoning steps overflow the context window. Small local models typically have limited context windows, making them unable to maintain the full state needed for extended tasks.\n\n## Reliability Decay Over Task Horizons\n\nReliability decay is universal and pronounced, with all 10 models showing net decline in pass@1 from short to very-long horizons, with a mean drop of 24.3 percentage points (76.3% → 52.1%) over the four-bucket span. This demonstrates how error compounding becomes increasingly problematic as tasks extend.\n\n## Long-Horizon Planning Failures\n\nFrameworks pitched as \"fully autonomous\" still drift into circular tool calls, hallucinate file paths, or get stuck on long-horizon planning. Smaller models lack the capacity for sophisticated planning needed across multiple steps.\n\n## Model Capability Thresholds\n\nModels like Qwen3-Coder 30B, GLM-5.1 32B, Gemma 4 27B, and Llama 3.3 70B emit clean tool calls in every reliable stack, while models under 7B fail. This indicates a significant capability gap below certain parameter thresholds.\n\n## Practical Limitations of \"Autonomous\" Systems\n\nReliable stacks like Cline + Ollama and Continue.dev Agent mode succeed because they are scoped—one editor, one model, one approval gate—not because the underlying technology is good enough for unattended autonomy."],"durationSeconds":11.31321700000018,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"41594bb8-650d-4720-a849-bfd080f1443e","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
