{"parentUuid":"38bd17c6-cf8f-4844-8bc0-fb8a25f9bb2b","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"b83cd85c-215e-4dfb-b12b-82fa27341e0f","agentId":"a6867b8fa220460c5","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01DYBhBCcTZAeRVNeC5tWZyK","type":"tool_result","content":"# Key Headline Numbers from METR Report\n\n**Doubling Period:** \"with a doubling time of around 7 months\"\n\n**Best Model Time Horizon:** Claude 3.7 Sonnet achieves \"approximately one hour\" at 50% success rate on tasks.\n\n**Month-Long Tasks Extrapolation:** The analysis projects that \"if the measured trend from the past 6 years continues for 2-4 more years, generalist autonomous agents will be capable of performing a wide range of week-long tasks.\" More specifically, the sensitivity analysis suggests frontier systems could handle month-long work by the early-to-mid 2030s based on the exponential trend."}]},"uuid":"2029088a-b7fc-449c-8eeb-b3a45efe5a21","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:36:11.396Z","toolUseResult":{"bytes":107572,"code":200,"codeText":"OK","result":"# Key Headline Numbers from METR Report\n\n**Doubling Period:** \"with a doubling time of around 7 months\"\n\n**Best Model Time Horizon:** Claude 3.7 Sonnet achieves \"approximately one hour\" at 50% success rate on tasks.\n\n**Month-Long Tasks Extrapolation:** The analysis projects that \"if the measured trend from the past 6 years continues for 2-4 more years, generalist autonomous agents will be capable of performing a wide range of week-long tasks.\" More specifically, the sensitivity analysis suggests frontier systems could handle month-long work by the early-to-mid 2030s based on the exponential trend.","durationMs":6083,"url":"https://metr.org/blog/2025-03-19-measuring-ai-ability-to-complete-long-tasks/"},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"38bd17c6-cf8f-4844-8bc0-fb8a25f9bb2b","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"6a8ef2f2-5512-4593-a369-ccc80b09a045","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"b83cd85c-215e-4dfb-b12b-82fa27341e0f","agentId":"a6867b8fa220460c5","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01JxZzVyGJnzuLYpXDf1m9iU","type":"tool_result","content":"# Anthropic's View on Recursive Self-Improvement\n\n## Current Status\nAnthropic states they are \"not there yet\" regarding full recursive self-improvement, but acknowledge it \"could come sooner than most institutions are prepared for.\"\n\n## Timeline Projections\nThe article provides conditional forecasts rather than probability estimates:\n\n- **2027**: \"AI systems could be capable of tasks that take a person weeks\"\n- **Within one year**: Code quality expected to surpass human-written code at Anthropic\n- **Unspecified future**: \"In the future, agents could become capable enough to build and train models themselves\"\n\n## Key Quote on Feasibility\n\"It is genuinely unclear whether today's training methods and architectures could unlock that capacity.\" However, they note that most AI progress is incremental—\"exactly the kind of workflow Claude now excels at.\"\n\n## Three Scenarios\nAnthropic presents recursive self-improvement as one of three possible futures (scenario 3), without assigning explicit probabilities. They express uncertainty: \"We do not have good intuitions for what this world would look like.\"\n\n## Notable Caveat\nNo specific percentage likelihood is provided for recursive self-improvement occurring, reflecting genuine uncertainty about whether current scaling trends will continue or encounter diminishing returns."}]},"uuid":"b759b03b-9afe-44a2-852e-432176905d0e","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:36:13.862Z","toolUseResult":{"bytes":238474,"code":200,"codeText":"OK","result":"# Anthropic's View on Recursive Self-Improvement\n\n## Current Status\nAnthropic states they are \"not there yet\" regarding full recursive self-improvement, but acknowledge it \"could come sooner than most institutions are prepared for.\"\n\n## Timeline Projections\nThe article provides conditional forecasts rather than probability estimates:\n\n- **2027**: \"AI systems could be capable of tasks that take a person weeks\"\n- **Within one year**: Code quality expected to surpass human-written code at Anthropic\n- **Unspecified future**: \"In the future, agents could become capable enough to build and train models themselves\"\n\n## Key Quote on Feasibility\n\"It is genuinely unclear whether today's training methods and architectures could unlock that capacity.\" However, they note that most AI progress is incremental—\"exactly the kind of workflow Claude now excels at.\"\n\n## Three Scenarios\nAnthropic presents recursive self-improvement as one of three possible futures (scenario 3), without assigning explicit probabilities. They express uncertainty: \"We do not have good intuitions for what this world would look like.\"\n\n## Notable Caveat\nNo specific percentage likelihood is provided for recursive self-improvement occurring, reflecting genuine uncertainty about whether current scaling trends will continue or encounter diminishing returns.","durationMs":6220,"url":"https://www.anthropic.com/institute/recursive-self-improvement"},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"6a8ef2f2-5512-4593-a369-ccc80b09a045","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"32f23a34-bc2e-411c-afb2-9ada98b71add","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"b83cd85c-215e-4dfb-b12b-82fa27341e0f","agentId":"a6867b8fa220460c5","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_017JwwkSHPpLTnTymt2s3NL7","type":"tool_result","content":"Web search results for query: \"\"half-life\" AI agents constant hazard rate per-step failure exponential decay task length METR 2025\"\n\nLinks: [{\"title\":\"AI Agent Reliability: Exponential Decay and Task Design | WeSpeakAI\",\"url\":\"https://www.wespeak.ai/aiagentblog/ai-agent-reliability:-exponential-decay-and-task-design\"},{\"title\":\"1 Is there a half-life for the success rates of AI agents? Toby Ord\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2505.05115\"},{\"title\":\"Is there a half-life for the success rates of AI agents? | alphaXiv\",\"url\":\"https://www.alphaxiv.org/overview/2505.05115v1\"},{\"title\":\"Is There a Half-Life for the Success Rates of AI Agents?\",\"url\":\"https://www.forethought.org/research/is-there-a-half-life-for-the-success-rates-of-ai-agents\"},{\"title\":\"Half-Life Crisis: Why AI Agents Fade with Time (and What It Means for Automation) | Cognaptus\",\"url\":\"https://cognaptus.com/blog/2025-05-11-halflife-crisis-why-ai-agents-fade-with-time-and-what-it-means-for-automation/\"},{\"title\":\"Is there a Half-Life for the Success Rates of AI Agents? — Toby Ord\",\"url\":\"https://www.tobyord.com/writing/half-life\"},{\"title\":\"The Half-Life Paradox: Why AI Agents Fail at Longer Tasks | by Divyansh Bhatia | Medium\",\"url\":\"https://medium.com/@divyanshbhatiajm19/the-half-life-paradox-why-ai-agents-fail-at-longer-tasks-43eee80f4fee\"},{\"title\":\"[Literature Review] Is there a half-life for the success rates of AI agents?\",\"url\":\"https://www.themoonlight.io/en/review/is-there-a-half-life-for-the-success-rates-of-ai-agents\"},{\"title\":\"Is there a Half-Life for the Success Rates of AI Agents? — EA Forum\",\"url\":\"https://forum.effectivealtruism.org/posts/qz3xyqCeriFHeTAJs/is-there-a-half-life-for-the-success-rates-of-ai-agents-3\"},{\"title\":\"[2505.05115] Is there a half-life for the success rates of AI agents?\",\"url\":\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2505.05115\"}]\n\nI found relevant information about AI agent half-life and exponential decay. Here are the key findings:\n\n## Core Research Finding\n\nBuilding on research by Kwa et al. (2025) from METR, AI agent performance on longer-duration tasks can be explained by a constant rate of failing during each minute a human would take to do the task. METR found an exponential trend where every 7 months, the length of task frontier AI agents can solve doubles.\n\n## Half-Life and Constant Hazard Rate\n\nPerformance of AI agents on longer-duration tasks can be explained by a constant rate of failing during each minute a human would take to do the task, which implies an exponentially declining success rate with the length of the task and that each agent could be characterised by its own half-life.\n\nA constant hazard rate means that the chance of something failing in the next step (conditional on making it that far) is constant, and a constant hazard rate leads to an exponentially declining survival curve.\n\n## Mathematical Model\n\nLonger tasks involve an increasing number of sequential subtasks, and failing at any one subtask leads to failure of the entire task, which is mathematically equivalent to saying that the probability of success is the product of the probabilities of succeeding at each subtask.\n\n## Progress Over Time\n\nThe \"half-life\" (time for success rate to drop to 50%) of top AI agents is doubling approximately every 7 months, indicating exponential progress in agent endurance across tasks like cybersecurity, ML coding, and reasoning.\n\n\nREMINDER: You MUST include the sources above in your response to the user using markdown hyperlinks."}]},"uuid":"06d729c9-b391-4f97-9918-0597931293a8","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:36:17.897Z","toolUseResult":{"query":"\"half-life\" AI agents constant hazard rate per-step failure exponential decay task length METR 2025","results":[{"tool_use_id":"srvtoolu_01G5bqmxCuPdDWwH6Zd1rZdz","content":[{"title":"AI Agent Reliability: Exponential Decay and Task Design | WeSpeakAI","url":"https://www.wespeak.ai/aiagentblog/ai-agent-reliability:-exponential-decay-and-task-design"},{"title":"1 Is there a half-life for the success rates of AI agents? Toby Ord","url":"https://arxiv.org/pdf/2505.05115"},{"title":"Is there a half-life for the success rates of AI agents? | alphaXiv","url":"https://www.alphaxiv.org/overview/2505.05115v1"},{"title":"Is There a Half-Life for the Success Rates of AI Agents?","url":"https://www.forethought.org/research/is-there-a-half-life-for-the-success-rates-of-ai-agents"},{"title":"Half-Life Crisis: Why AI Agents Fade with Time (and What It Means for Automation) | Cognaptus","url":"https://cognaptus.com/blog/2025-05-11-halflife-crisis-why-ai-agents-fade-with-time-and-what-it-means-for-automation/"},{"title":"Is there a Half-Life for the Success Rates of AI Agents? — Toby Ord","url":"https://www.tobyord.com/writing/half-life"},{"title":"The Half-Life Paradox: Why AI Agents Fail at Longer Tasks | by Divyansh Bhatia | Medium","url":"https://medium.com/@divyanshbhatiajm19/the-half-life-paradox-why-ai-agents-fail-at-longer-tasks-43eee80f4fee"},{"title":"[Literature Review] Is there a half-life for the success rates of AI agents?","url":"https://www.themoonlight.io/en/review/is-there-a-half-life-for-the-success-rates-of-ai-agents"},{"title":"Is there a Half-Life for the Success Rates of AI Agents? — EA Forum","url":"https://forum.effectivealtruism.org/posts/qz3xyqCeriFHeTAJs/is-there-a-half-life-for-the-success-rates-of-ai-agents-3"},{"title":"[2505.05115] Is there a half-life for the success rates of AI agents?","url":"https://arxiv.org/abs/2505.05115"}]},"I found relevant information about AI agent half-life and exponential decay. Here are the key findings:\n\n## Core Research Finding\n\nBuilding on research by Kwa et al. (2025) from METR, AI agent performance on longer-duration tasks can be explained by a constant rate of failing during each minute a human would take to do the task. METR found an exponential trend where every 7 months, the length of task frontier AI agents can solve doubles.\n\n## Half-Life and Constant Hazard Rate\n\nPerformance of AI agents on longer-duration tasks can be explained by a constant rate of failing during each minute a human would take to do the task, which implies an exponentially declining success rate with the length of the task and that each agent could be characterised by its own half-life.\n\nA constant hazard rate means that the chance of something failing in the next step (conditional on making it that far) is constant, and a constant hazard rate leads to an exponentially declining survival curve.\n\n## Mathematical Model\n\nLonger tasks involve an increasing number of sequential subtasks, and failing at any one subtask leads to failure of the entire task, which is mathematically equivalent to saying that the probability of success is the product of the probabilities of succeeding at each subtask.\n\n## Progress Over Time\n\nThe \"half-life\" (time for success rate to drop to 50%) of top AI agents is doubling approximately every 7 months, indicating exponential progress in agent endurance across tasks like cybersecurity, ML coding, and reasoning."],"durationSeconds":11.441736999999732,"searchCount":1},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"32f23a34-bc2e-411c-afb2-9ada98b71add","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
